Defendant Cedric A Ivory in court with attorney James Edgar Toran.  Defendant Cedric A Ivory in custody.  Jeremy R. Arn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, defense, and defendant. 

COUNT 1:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 4 YEARS, CONCURRENT to 14CF000793, CONSECUTIVE to any other time with credit for 55 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 18 MONTHS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 30 MONTHS.

The defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.  The defendant IS eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*Obtain AODA assessment and successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Take any prescription medication only in the manner/dosage as prescribed by a treating physician;
*Cooperate with random urine screens;
*No drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers or drug houses);
*Cooperate with any and all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*No contact with Sam's Club located at 1540 S. 108th St., West Allis;
*Obtain/maintain part time employment;
*Participate in vocational training;
*Participate in Cognitive thinking;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample- pay surcharge;
*Pay all applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs- bail to apply after restitution on case 14CF000793 paid in full from bail; 

State in compliance with victim rights legislation.  The Court orders bail on this case to apply towards restitution ordered in case 14CF000793.  The Court orders the balance of the bail held pending restitution hearing in case 14CF000793.  The Court ordered that all financial obligations and restitution be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  Appeal rights given.
